column36: Facilitators built trust with participants. Everyone was well engaged!

column35: Time spent where poster in curriculum did not correspond to the activity. This is the fault of ETR.

- There was not enough time to complete the session  - Participants came and went (started with 4, half left at 9am, then 2 more joined a couple of minutes later). This could make keeping attendance, fidelity, and make up lessons difficult to keep track of.   - Seemed rushed at times, maybe try and find a longer time period where all activities in module can be taught at same time.
column36: - Great job at validating participant's feelings and needs  - Very engaged and active group  - Facilitator was great at engaging young people
column37: - Suggest having an anonymous question box available  - Suggest posting group guidelines  - Suggest changing gendered language in curriculum in order to be more inclusive.

column35: Pay attention to gendered language. Instead of saying "you guys" say "y'all" or something similar.
column36: Facilitators were confident and made participants feel comfortable. Timing was excellent.
column37: Facilitators also successfully implemented the supplemental lesson on consent: Tell me how you Like it.

column35: Some technical issue from me being virtual but I could hear well. Ms. McLeod was confident and participants were engaged
column36: Ms. Mcleod offered words of encouragement throughout and is really making the program her own!

column35: Due to observation being done online but session was in person, it was difficult to hear and see everyone. This is a technical issue and one that will be resolved when we are all in person again.     I did notice some time management challenges that can be easily fixed.
column37: Maybe play music while students work in pairs or in groups, liked the timer going off (great idea!), asked students to pass around handouts which got them involved, liked that the students had fidget toys, and I enjoyed watching Mr. Turner teach! Looks like it is going well :)
